@article{Mai2013,
abstract = {Executive Summary$\backslash$nThe desire for a ``crystal ball'' to peer into the future has perhaps never been stronger$\backslash$namong energy and environmental planners. While the future has always been uncertain,$\backslash$nthe interconnectedness of modern economic systems serves to enhance the ripple effect$\backslash$nof our energy actions. Today's decisions also seem to be made under heightened$\backslash$nuncertainty, as demonstrated by the number of recent unexpected events, such as: a$\backslash$nprolonged economic recession, an unfolding shale energy revolution, the Fukushima$\backslash$ndisaster, the Arab Spring, and a notable reduction in photovoltaic costs. Policymakers have$\backslash$nhistorically relied on energy scenarios and modeling to help inform decision making. While$\backslash$nthere exists a wealth of advanced model, data, and energy scenario options, important$\backslash$nquestions remain about how to effectively apply these tools to help plan for an$\backslash$nuncertain future.$\backslash$nEnergy scenarios use varying techniques and approaches to consider alternative energy$\backslash$nfutures. They help prepare for decision making under uncertainty and inform policy$\backslash$noptions that society may desire. Most energy scenarios rely on quantitative models---often$\backslash$nhighly complex---to compare tradeoffs and quantify specific outcomes of different courses$\backslash$nof action. Energy models are abstractions of reality that simplify the world into ``bite sized''$\backslash$npieces in order to fit within certain sets of mathematic methodologies. They range in scale$\backslash$nfrom the local to global, in sector from electricity- or transportation-only to economywide.$\backslash$nThey simulate, optimize, or equilibrate; forecast; and help plan. Some are used for$\backslash$nacademic purposes, others for policy, regulatory, or investment planning. All models rely$\backslash$non imperfect inputs, parameters, assumptions, and interpretation. They all contain$\backslash$nstructural compromises, simplifications, and omissions. One must maintain a spirit of$\backslash$nhumility about predictions, particularly when asked to look decades into the future.$\backslash$nKnowledge and cultural gaps that exist among policymakers, scenario developers, and$\backslash$nenergy modelers can also result in misunderstanding of modeling results. This study$\backslash$nattempts to help bridge some of those gaps so that stakeholders can use energy scenario$\backslash$nresults more effectively. It also functions as a support guide for preparing or$\backslash$ncommissioning energy scenario analyses.$\backslash$nThe ``Top 10'' key findings from this study are summarized here.$\backslash$n1. Do not expect a model or energy scenario to predict the future.$\backslash$nNo model can predict the future, but this is often forgotten. The further an energy$\backslash$nscenario looks into the future, the more uncertainty is introduced. Single scenarios$\backslash$nare rarely helpful, but must be combined with, and compared against, diverse$\backslash$nalternatives as part of a larger strategic exercise.$\backslash$n2. Match the model to the problem.$\backslash$nThere are almost as many types of energy models as there are questions about our$\backslash$nenergy future. Make sure the question you want to answer is well-formed, and$\backslash$nthen pick the right type of model to best address it. For the simplest example, an$\backslash$nelectricity sector-only model should not be chosen to address an economy-wide$\backslash$ngreenhouse gas mitigation question.$\backslash$n3. Make assumptions and accounting frameworks transparent.$\backslash$nModels require thousands, and often millions, of pieces of input data. The meaning$\backslash$nof these data needs to be clearly understood by all. What type of energy$\backslash$naccounting methodology is used? How do technology cost and performance$\backslash$nassumptions change over time? Are the economic data measured in current or real$\backslash$nvalues? Is traditional biomass included or only modern biomass? To address these$\backslash$nand other potential misinterpretations, all assumptions should be clearly and$\backslash$ntransparently articulated. Without transparency, credibility is sacrificed and results$\backslash$ncan misinform.$\backslash$n4. Understand the limitations of how human behavior is represented.$\backslash$nA typical energy model finds a solution based on the overall system's equilibrium$\backslash$n(matching of supply and demand) or least-cost point. However, real-world$\backslash$nproducers and consumers often find themselves out of equilibrium, and agreement$\backslash$non a system-wide optimal point is rare. Institutional, jurisdictional, supply chain$\backslash$nbottlenecks, or social barriers such as {\{}$\backslash$dq{\}}not in my backyard{\{}$\backslash$dq{\}} attitudes can prevent$\backslash$nthe system from reaching these ideal points. The potential for humans to change$\backslash$ntheir behavior in unexpected ways is also commonly not factored into models.$\backslash$nEnergy models are typically better at characterizing supply-side options than they$\backslash$nare those on the demand-side, particularly related to energy efficiency behavior.$\backslash$n5. Use diverse tools and approaches to address uncertainty.$\backslash$nUncertainty about the future comes in different forms. Some is ``characterizable''$\backslash$nwhile others are not (known unknowns and unknown unknowns). New analytic$\backslash$napproaches are available to help address some classes of risk and uncertainty.$\backslash$nModelers can use a variety of techniques, often borrowed from the financial$\backslash$nliterature---Monte Carlo simulations, real options and portfolio theory, for$\backslash$nexample---to better characterize uncertainty. For ``uncharacterizable'' uncertainty,$\backslash$nscenarios should be designed to consider the potential impacts of certain families$\backslash$nof unexpected events or ``black swans'' (e.g., a disruptive technology innovation).$\backslash$n6. Consider how unique traits of renewable energy are modeled.$\backslash$nHigher resolution is required to model the site-specificity, and variable and$\backslash$nuncertain nature of many renewables. Constrained by computational limits,$\backslash$nmodelers are forced into trade-offs between increasing their geographic and time$\backslash$nresolution, or simplifying other aspects of the energy economy. Because of the$\backslash$nunique traits of renewables, transparency in their assumptions and model$\backslash$ntreatment is necessary to better understand if they are treated appropriately and$\backslash$nwhether the playing field is level. In particular, renewable technologies should be$\backslash$nviewed within the larger energy system and not be forced to fit within the confines$\backslash$nof the status quo technologies or operational practices, (e.g. some models$\backslash$nerroneously use a one-to-one {\{}$\backslash$dq{\}}back-up{\{}$\backslash$dq{\}} requirement for each variable renewable$\backslash$npower generation technology).$\backslash$n7. Communicate effectively and appropriately.$\backslash$nEnergy modeling is a highly specialized endeavor. What modelers consider$\backslash$n``results'' and what decision makers deem useful information may not overlap. The$\backslash$ncommunication of results is inherently difficult. The two communities would$\backslash$nbenefit by better understanding the challenges and opportunities that exist for$\backslash$neach other. Modelers should put themselves in the shoes of policymakers when$\backslash$ncommunicating results and synthesize findings at an ``appropriate'' level of detail.$\backslash$nDefining vocabulary in simple terms can help this ``translation'' from one world to$\backslash$nanother.$\backslash$n8. Expect bias and learn to identify its traits.$\backslash$nAll modeling approaches incorporate bias, either accidentally or purposefully.$\backslash$nConsumers of energy scenarios can learn to identify scenario, data, and model$\backslash$nsubjectivity, and take steps to ensure appropriate interpretation. Commissioners of$\backslash$nenergy scenarios should use diverse networks of expert reviewers to address real$\backslash$nand perceived bias before results are finalized.$\backslash$n9. Consider energy scenarios with limited or no modeling.$\backslash$nCommissioners of energy scenarios should consider broad stakeholder$\backslash$nengagements that focus on ``upstream'' discussion of assumptions and desired$\backslash$noutcomes as a first step before modeling. Focusing limited resources on these$\backslash$ndiscussions with ``back of the envelope'' calculations can provide unique value.$\backslash$nModeling can be a subsequent step after the stakeholder dialogues to provide$\backslash$nadditional useful insights.$\backslash$n10. Conduct retrospective analysis to better understand energy scenario misses and$\backslash$nhits.$\backslash$nToo often, energy stakeholders do not go back to revisit why certain energy$\backslash$nscenarios were so far off the mark or why they provided unexpectedly valuable$\backslash$ninformation. There is value ``left on the table'' by not returning more often to$\backslash$nprevious energy scenarios to analyze why they did or didn't work well.$\backslash$nThese findings are principles---they are not comprehensive, nor do they apply in all cases.$\backslash$nWe hope this document will help catalyze and inform discussion and debate among$\backslash$nstakeholders on how to improve the value of energy scenarios.},
author = {Mai, Trieu and Logan, Jeffrey and Blair, Nate and Sullivan, Patrick and Bazilian, Morgan},
file = {:Users/alexanderkell/Documents/Mendeley Desktop/RE-ASSUME{\_}IEA-RETD{\_}20131.pdf:pdf},
